Code Page 932 Encoding and Decoding

Published August 07, 2024
By Samuel Yang

Code Page 932 (CP932), also known as Windows-31J or Shift_JIS, is a character encoding system used to represent Japanese text in Microsoft Windows. It is an extension of Shift JIS (Shift Japanese Industrial Standards) and includes additional characters to support more comprehensive usage in Japanese computing environments.

Code Page 932 (CP932) uses different byte sequences to represent different types of characters:

  • Single-Byte Characters
    The valid lead byte ranges for single-byte sequences are as follows:
    • 0x00-0x7F
    • 0xA1-0xDF
  • Two-Byte Characters
    The valid lead byte ranges for double-byte sequences are as follows:
    • 0x81-0x9F
    • 0xE0-0xFC


    The valid trail byte ranges for double-byte sequences are as follows:
    • 0x40-0x7E
    • 0x80-0xFC

Code Page 932 (CP932) includes characters from:

  • ASCII occupy the range 0x00-0x7F
  • JIS X 0201 (half-width Katakana) occupy the range 0xA1-0xDF
  • JIS X 0208 (Kanji characters) occupy the range 0x889F-0x9872. It includes over 6,000 kanji characters, covering the most commonly used characters in Japanese
  • NEC special characters occupy the ranges:
    • 0x8740-0x879E: This range includes various special symbols, often used in Japanese computing and telecommunication contexts
    • 0xFA40-0xFAFC: Additional kanji and symbols not covered by the standard JIS X 0208 character set
    • 0xFB40-0xFBFC: More supplementary kanji and symbols
    • 0xFC40-0xFC4B: This is a smaller set of additional special characters
  • NEC selection of IBM extensions occupy the ranges:
    • 0xED40-0xED7E: This range includes a variety of special symbols and kanji characters
    • 0xED80-0xED9E: This range continues with additional symbols and kanji characters
  • IBM extensions occupy the ranges:
    • 0xFA40-0xFAFC: This range contains additional kanji and symbols not included in the standard JIS X 0208 character set
    • 0xFB40-0xFBFC: This range continues with more kanji and special symbols, expanding the repertoire of characters available in the encoding
    • 0xFC40-0xFC4B: This is a smaller subset that includes some final additional characters, often specialized or less commonly used

The Private Use Area (PUA) refers to a specific range of code points reserved for user-defined characters that are not part of the standard character sets defined by JIS X 0208 or other official standards. This allows for the inclusion of custom or specialized characters that are specific to particular applications or organizations.

The Private Use Area in CP932 is located within the following ranges:

  • Lead Byte Ranges: 0xE0-0xFC
  • Trail Byte Ranges: 0x40-0xFE
